You are given two integer arrays nums1 and nums2, sorted in non-decreasing order, and two integers m and n, representing the number of elements in nums1 and nums2 respectively.

Merge nums1 and nums2 into a single array sorted in non-decreasing order.

The final sorted array should not be returned by the function, but instead be stored inside the array nums1.
To accommodate this, nums1 has a length of m + n, where the first m elements denote the elements that should be merged, and the last n elements are set to 0 and should be ignored. nums2 has a length of n.





intuition - In nums1 after mth element there are 0, those 0s are equal to n.SO iterate over n and convert every (m+i) element of nums1 to ith element of nums2. Atlast return the sorted array





class Solution(object):
    def merge(self, nums1, m, nums2, n):
      for i in range(n):
          nums1[m+i] = nums2[i]
      nums1.sort()



java solution - used 2 pointers. Give better time complexity(logN) than using sort after placing them in array(N logN).
                as it is given these are non decreasing array we can copare the biggest(last) values of each array and place whuchever is bigger in the first array, and keep going until one of the constraint is
                broken.



class Solution {
    public void merge(int[] nums1, int m, int[] nums2, int n) {
        int i=m-1,j=n-1,k=m+n-1;
        while(j>=0){
            if (i>=0 && nums1[i]>nums2[j]){
                nums1[k]=nums1[i];
                k--;
                i--;
            }
            else{
                nums1[k]=nums2[j];
                k--;
                j--;
            }
        }
    }
}
